Project: Analysing Movie Data¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

The TMDb dataset was chosen for this project. This data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue. We will conduct som data wrangling and then answer a set of questions about the data.

Following questions will be answered in the course of this analysis:

General questions:

  • Which year had the highest votes on average?
  • Has there been an increase in movie entries for tmdb?
  • How have movie ratings developed over the course of the years?
  • Which directors produced most movies?

Research questions:

  • Research Question 1: Which genres are most popular from year to year?
  • Research Question 2: What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?
  • Research question 3: Are movies from before 2000 better than after 2000?

Data Cleaning¶

We will clean the data by removing duplicates, zero values, rows with too many NaN values and also remove outliers. While cleaning we also want to maintain the largest amount of data.

There is one duplicate row in the data set which is removed with the following command:

In [9]:
df.drop_duplicates(inplace=True)

There are no duplicated IDs left!

In [10]:
df.id.duplicated().sum() # check whether we have duplicate ID's which is even stricter than looking for duplicate rows.
Out[10]:
0

The 'homepage' column has a lot of NaN values and provides little analytical relevance. Therefore, it can be dropped:

In [11]:
df.drop('homepage', axis=1, inplace=True)

Also drop unadjusted revenue and budget counts as they are less usable for comparing. We will use the adjusted values instead.

In [17]:
df_clean = df.drop('revenue', axis=1)
df_clean.drop('budget', axis=1, inplace=True)
In [18]:

In [19]:
df_clean = df_clean[df_clean.budget_adj > 0] # clean dataset by removing rows with movies which have no budget data

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Now that we've trimmed and cleaned our data, we're ready to move on to exploration. In this section we will compute statistics and create visualizations. We will also pose some research question. It is recommended that you be systematic with your approach. Look at one variable at a time, and then follow it up by looking at relationships between variables.

Let's do some correlation analysis first to find out about the relation between variables:

In [25]:
scatter_matrix(df_clean, alpha=0.2, figsize=(16, 16), diagonal='kde');

Vote average has characteristics of a normal distribution! Runtime is slightly skewed to the right.

In [26]:
corr = df_clean.corr()
sns.heatmap(corr, 
            xticklabels=corr.columns.values,
            yticklabels=corr.columns.values);

Let's see if investments in producing movies generally pay off. Does the budget correlate with the final revenue?

In [27]:
df_clean.plot('budget_adj', 'revenue_adj', kind='scatter');
In [28]:
np.corrcoef(df_clean.budget_adj, df_clean.revenue_adj)[0,1]
Out[28]:
0.58480027103752175

Looking at the correlation coefficient and the plot, there is a positive correlation between budget and revenue.

But does the budget also correlate with the user rating?

In [29]:
df_clean.plot('vote_average', 'budget_adj', kind='scatter');
In [30]:
np.corrcoef(df_clean.vote_average, df_clean.budget_adj)[0,1]
Out[30]:
-0.019093818433324472

No, the two variables do not correlate. Putting more money into a movie does not mean it can buy a higher rating.

Does the revenue have a relation to the user rating?

In [31]:
df_clean.plot('vote_average', 'revenue_adj', kind='scatter');
In [32]:
np.corrcoef(df_clean.vote_average, df_clean.revenue_adj)[0,1]
Out[32]:
0.22139705757213696

There is a slight correlation between users liking the movie and paying for it.

Looking at the vote average, we can see the distribution is approximately normal:

In [33]:
df_clean.vote_average.plot(kind='hist');

Has there been an increase in movie entries for tmdb?

In [34]:
df.groupby('release_year')['id'].count().plot(kind='line');

We can see as strong uptrend of tmdb growing over the years. The decrease in the current year indicates the year not having ended yet.

We want to have a score for popularity for each genre, so we need to get the average popularity per genre per year. To achieve that, we multiply the popularity with each dummy variable. Subsequently, we group by ID and year. The genre having the maximum average score is regarded as teh most popular!

(1) multiply popularity with each genre for each movie

In [49]:
pop = df1.columns[2] # get popularity column
gcols = df1.columns[3:] # get genre columns
for g in gcols: # for each genre columns
    df1[g] *= df1[pop] # multiply popularity score with dummy value

General findings:¶

- Movies with high revenue also have a high budget of arount 80M on average, but with a quite high standard deviation of 5.5M.
- They run around 116 minutes so they come close to two hours which is longer than the average movie.
- High grossing movies have a higher vote average.
- They are slighly older

Research question 3: Are movies from before 2000 better than after 2000?¶

To answer this question, let's split the dataset up into two categories:

movies released before 2000 and after 2000

Calculating the vote_average, it turns out that movies after 2000 have a slightly lower rating than before 2000. Let's test for statistic significance using a T-test:

In [74]:
cat1 = df3.query("after_2000 == True")
cat2 = df3.query("after_2000 == False")

ttest_ind(cat2.vote_average, cat1.vote_average)
Out[74]:
Ttest_indResult(statistic=9.812039641435133, pvalue=1.2407748897486369e-22)

The t-statistic indicates that the difference between the two sets is around 9.81 times higher than the difference of the elements within each set. What is more, the p-value is very small, which indicates that movies before 2000 have siginficantly higher vote averages than after 2000!

Conclusions¶

Following steps have been conducted as part of the analysis:

The dataset has been checked for its general properties and cleaned in terms of duplicates, zero or NaN values and outliers. Also some exploratory statistics have been conducted.

In the context of the first research question it was found, that the 'drama' genre is the most popular genre over many years. Within the scope of the second question it was shown what the characteristics of movies are, which generate high revenues: The are genrerally more expensive, have longer runtimes and are rated better by the audience. The third question compares movie rating between movies before and after 2000 and comes to the conclusion that movies before 2000 have significantly higher ratings than after.

Limitations:¶

The vote averages have not been weighted amongst the number of votes. Many movies did not have data for revenue or budget which decreases the size of the data set. Drama is the most 'popular' genre, however more than one genre were assigned to most movies and it seems that most movies have the characteristics of a drama. E.g. a movie can be an action movie but is also a drama. Or it can be comedy and a drama. A further question arises, if 'drama' can be regarded as a real genre or if almost every movie has drama elements in them, meaning that 'drama' would not make a good match for a genre category.
